#!/usr/bin/env bashi
A Media Access Control (MAC) address is a unique identifier assigned to the network interface controller (NIC) for communication at the data link layer of a network. It is typically represented as a 48-bit hexadecimal number.
An Internet Protocol (IP) address is a numerical label assigned to each device connected to a network, used for identifying and locating the device. There are two versions: IPv4 (32-bit) and IPv6 (128-bit).
